1
00:00:04,163 --> 00:00:08,148
Remember when you were a kid,
and your biggest worry was,

2
00:00:08,210 --> 00:00:10,939
like, if you'd get a bike for your birthday

3
00:00:11,001 --> 00:00:13,729
or if you'd get to eat cookies for breakfast?

4
00:00:14,563 --> 00:00:17,670
Being an adult - totally overrated.

5
00:00:19,954 --> 00:00:23,944
I mean, seriously, don't be fooled by
all the hot shoes and the great sex

6
00:00:24,004 --> 00:00:26,477
and the no parents anywhere
telling you what to do.

7
00:00:28,121 --> 00:00:30,506
Adulthood is responsibility.

8
00:00:31,024 --> 00:00:33,636
The lawyer has been managing her estate
with a limited power of attorney,

9
00:00:33,681 --> 00:00:35,831
but your mother's alzheimer's is advancing.

10
00:00:35,883 --> 00:00:37,992
So, while she's still lucid enough to consent,

11
00:00:38,040 --> 00:00:39,988
she needs to sign everything over to you.

12
00:00:42,068 --> 00:00:42,882
Me?

13
00:00:46,077 --> 00:00:49,231
Responsibility - it really does suck.

14
00:00:49,303 --> 00:00:52,022
Look, I haven't slept in 48 hours.

15
00:00:52,099 --> 00:00:54,977
I'm getting my first shot at
heart surgery this morning.

16
00:00:55,109 --> 00:00:56,430
I'm missing rounds.

17
00:00:56,563 --> 00:01:00,762
Are you sure there isn't anybody
here, or the attorney...?

18
00:01:00,996 --> 00:01:03,686
I mean, do I really have to
be the one to handle this?

19
00:01:03,782 --> 00:01:06,849
We're talking about her estate,
finances, medical care.

20
00:01:06,896 --> 00:01:09,035
You really want to leave her
life in someone else's hands?

21
00:01:09,087 --> 00:01:10,142
She's your mother.

22
00:01:11,836 --> 00:01:14,007
Really, really sucks.

23
00:01:15,534 --> 00:01:18,564
Adults have to be places and do things

24
00:01:18,605 --> 00:01:21,647
and earn a living and pay the rent.

25
00:01:21,891 --> 00:01:23,643
And if you're training to be a surgeon,

26
00:01:23,833 --> 00:01:26,065
holding a human heart in your hands -

27
00:01:27,360 --> 00:01:30,825
Hello! Talk about responsibility!

28
00:01:34,145 --> 00:01:35,378
What was that, Dr. Grey?

29
00:01:35,435 --> 00:01:37,027
Sorry, it slipped.

30
00:01:37,104 --> 00:01:37,917
My hands...

31
00:01:38,497 --> 00:01:39,777
It's okay. I'm done.

32
00:01:40,344 --> 00:01:42,214
You can release Mrs. Patterson's heart now,

33
00:01:42,691 --> 00:01:43,800
very gently.

34
00:01:47,754 --> 00:01:48,623
All right.

35
00:01:49,322 --> 00:01:50,492
Let's warm her up.

36
00:01:51,036 --> 00:01:52,020
Get her off bypass.

37
00:01:52,075 --> 00:01:55,377
Kind of makes bikes and cookies look
really, really good, doesn't it?

38
00:01:55,608 --> 00:01:57,279
I wish I could hold a heart.

39
00:01:57,359 --> 00:01:58,746
A monkey could hold a heart.

40
00:01:59,423 --> 00:02:01,086
You're mad Burke didn't ask you.

41
00:02:01,157 --> 00:02:03,489
George, I need more ice and chips.

42
00:02:03,555 --> 00:02:04,542
Who did you invite?

43
00:02:04,621 --> 00:02:08,418
We said the list was jocks only
- surgery, trauma, plastics.

44
00:02:08,480 --> 00:02:09,248
Who else?

45
00:02:09,447 --> 00:02:10,753
Some people from peds.

46
00:02:11,423 --> 00:02:13,769
You invited the preschoolers to Meredith's house.

47
00:02:13,830 --> 00:02:16,226
Next thing, you'll say that
you invited the shrinks.

48
00:02:17,614 --> 00:02:19,197
She invited mental defects.

49
00:02:19,410 --> 00:02:20,440
This party is D.O.A.

50
00:02:20,507 --> 00:02:24,244
Meredith thinks this is going to be a
small, meet-your-boyfriend cocktail thing.

51
00:02:24,300 --> 00:02:25,300
Did you clear this with her?

52
00:02:25,364 --> 00:02:26,262
No, but I will.

53
00:02:27,424 --> 00:02:28,525
I promise.

54
00:02:28,632 --> 00:02:32,216
Why are you wasting the only weekend your
boyfriend is in town on a big party?

55
00:02:32,519 --> 00:02:33,629
Is he bad in bed?

56
00:02:34,740 --> 00:02:37,348
No. I just want him to meet some of my friends.

57
00:02:37,413 --> 00:02:40,680
Right. 60 geeks in scrubs are your friends.

58
00:02:43,061 --> 00:02:44,698
Bad sex - sucks for you.

59
00:02:44,771 --> 00:02:46,686
I heard there's a party tonight.
At Meredith's house.

60
00:02:46,789 --> 00:02:48,775
- A party?
- Uh, news to me.

61
00:02:48,851 --> 00:02:49,568
No party.

62
00:02:49,649 --> 00:02:50,843
We losing her or what?

63
00:02:51,959 --> 00:02:53,372
- Are the grafts...?
- They're open.

64
00:02:53,649 --> 00:02:56,536
- Temperature?
- She's at 96 and rising.

65
00:02:56,614 --> 00:02:58,139
She should be doing this on her own.

66
00:03:02,015 --> 00:03:03,064
That's her falling.

67
00:03:04,381 --> 00:03:05,630
Continue the progressions.

68
00:03:08,497 --> 00:03:09,839
Come on, Mrs. Patterson.

69
00:03:09,910 --> 00:03:11,835
- Paddles.
- Sets are below 90.

70
00:03:12,225 --> 00:03:12,880
Charge.

71
00:03:14,058 --> 00:03:14,917
10 joules.

72
00:03:15,434 --> 00:03:16,193
Clear.

73
00:03:18,420 --> 00:03:19,751
Come on, Mrs. Patterson.

74
00:03:20,719 --> 00:03:21,932
- Give me 20.
- Charge.

75
00:03:22,249 --> 00:03:23,574
There. We have rhythm.

76
00:03:25,543 --> 00:03:26,878
Reluctant heart.

77
00:03:27,840 --> 00:03:28,655
All right.

78
00:03:29,479 --> 00:03:30,401
Let's close.

79
00:03:30,820 --> 00:03:31,731
Keep an eye on her.

80
00:03:32,335 --> 00:03:33,323
Good work, everyone.

81
00:03:34,783 --> 00:03:37,199
The scariest part about responsibility?

82
00:03:38,234 --> 00:03:43,006
When you screw up and let it
slip right through your fingers.

83
00:03:45,582 --> 00:03:48,100
Hey, I heard you did a cabg with Burke.

84
00:03:48,207 --> 00:03:49,253
Did you get to hold the heart?

85
00:03:49,485 --> 00:03:50,374
Yeah.

86
00:03:50,501 --> 00:03:53,287
It's an amazing feeling. You
never forget the first time.

87
00:03:53,430 --> 00:03:54,977
It was pretty great just to watch.

88
00:03:55,453 --> 00:03:57,239
Vicarious thrills, you know?

89
00:03:57,696 --> 00:03:58,499
Yeah.

90
00:04:05,135 --> 00:04:05,964
See you later.

91
00:04:06,338 --> 00:04:07,107
Bye.

92
00:04:18,223 --> 00:04:23,153
I think maybe I did something to
the heart when I was holding it.

93
00:04:24,054 --> 00:04:26,659
I nodded off a little, squeezed it.

94
00:04:27,955 --> 00:04:28,902
Oh, please.

95
00:04:29,061 --> 00:04:30,437
The heart's a tough muscle.

96
00:04:30,540 --> 00:04:32,573
It can take a squeeze or two.

97
00:04:32,988 --> 00:04:36,751
My fingernail popped a
glove, cut straight through.

98
00:04:37,612 --> 00:04:40,356
George, what if I punctured
Mrs. Patterson's heart?

99
00:04:43,019 --> 00:04:45,220
If you had punctured it,

100
00:04:46,428 --> 00:04:48,266
you would have known when they reperfused.

101
00:04:48,313 --> 00:04:50,253
They got her heart beating. The woman's okay.

102
00:04:51,304 --> 00:04:53,504
- So, I shouldn't tell Burke?
- Tell him what?

103
00:04:54,401 --> 00:04:55,398
You know, um...

104
00:04:56,607 --> 00:04:58,582
nothing happened. The woman's okay, right?

105
00:05:00,175 --> 00:05:01,183
She's okay.

106
00:05:01,850 --> 00:05:02,710
She's fine.

107
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:04,844
She's fine.

108
00:05:37,012 --> 00:05:38,141
What do you see, George?

109
00:05:38,272 --> 00:05:41,177
Hyperinflated lungs - cloudy with bullae.

110
00:05:41,679 --> 00:05:43,240
Seriously diminished capacity.

111
00:05:43,302 --> 00:05:45,288
She must be having trouble breathing.

112
00:05:46,036 --> 00:05:47,126
Course of action?

113
00:05:47,198 --> 00:05:50,721
A bullectomy procedure. Remove the bullae.
Reduce the pressure.

114
00:05:50,792 --> 00:05:53,102
It says here we operated on her back in '99.

115
00:05:53,153 --> 00:05:56,307
So Mrs. Drake has been through this
before, but talk her through it anyway.

116
00:05:56,384 --> 00:05:58,697
And resist the anti-smoking lectures.

117
00:05:58,789 --> 00:06:00,444
She feels bad enough already.

118
00:06:03,644 --> 00:06:05,601
So, do you think, if they
put a picture of these in

119
00:06:05,614 --> 00:06:07,582
a pack of cigarettes,
people would stop smoking?

120
00:06:11,421 --> 00:06:13,085
How long has your back been hurting you?

121
00:06:13,575 --> 00:06:14,990
It's chronic.

122
00:06:15,789 --> 00:06:17,228
Means I have it all the time.

123
00:06:17,283 --> 00:06:18,656
I know what "chronic" means.

124
00:06:18,792 --> 00:06:19,909
What kind of pain are you having?

125
00:06:19,987 --> 00:06:20,935
Oh, man, the pain's bad.

126
00:06:20,990 --> 00:06:24,830
It's like a thousand samurai warriors
stabbing their swords into my spine.

127
00:06:25,058 --> 00:06:27,263
I'm allergic to aspirin, most nsaids.

128
00:06:27,323 --> 00:06:28,584
So, maybe we'll start you on morphine.

129
00:06:29,080 --> 00:06:31,518
No. The only things that will work are, uh,

130
00:06:31,584 --> 00:06:35,839
demerol or dilaudid. A ton of
dilaudid - that will set me straight.

131
00:06:36,247 --> 00:06:38,359
The standard starting dose is two.

132
00:06:38,429 --> 00:06:40,621
Did you see that tom cruise samurai movie, hmm?

133
00:06:40,785 --> 00:06:42,147
Pow! Pow! Pow!

134
00:06:43,278 --> 00:06:46,032
Exaggerated and overly specific
description of his pain.

135
00:06:46,125 --> 00:06:47,334
A self-prescription.

136
00:06:48,040 --> 00:06:49,166
"Pow! Pow! Pow!"?

137
00:06:49,268 --> 00:06:50,503
He's a dilaudid junkie.

138
00:06:50,574 --> 00:06:51,425
So what do you do?

139
00:06:51,501 --> 00:06:54,629
Check the database for history,
refer to a program, and discharge.

140
00:06:54,717 --> 00:06:55,920
After you give him something.

141
00:06:56,473 --> 00:06:57,870
That's exactly what he wants.

142
00:06:57,938 --> 00:07:00,891
Junkie or not, you still have to
treat his pain as if it were real.

143
00:07:01,096 --> 00:07:01,699
Why?

144
00:07:01,767 --> 00:07:04,864
The first rule in pain management -
always ERR on the side of caution.

145
00:07:04,940 --> 00:07:06,808
He's in our care. He says he's in pain.

146
00:07:06,918 --> 00:07:09,112
Start a central line. His veins are shot.

147
00:07:17,477 --> 00:07:19,851
The surgery before was supposed to help.

148
00:07:20,584 --> 00:07:22,816
But it never felt right.

149
00:07:23,015 --> 00:07:25,083
Probably would have been a
good idea to quit smoking.

150
00:07:25,182 --> 00:07:26,328
I did!

151
00:07:26,563 --> 00:07:28,105
Four-pack-a-day habit.

152
00:07:28,351 --> 00:07:29,113
It was hell.

153
00:07:29,190 --> 00:07:30,214
Here you go, Mrs. Drake.

154
00:07:30,285 --> 00:07:31,546
Didn't do any good.

155
00:07:31,611 --> 00:07:33,321
Really? Because it looked...

156
00:07:33,420 --> 00:07:37,310
I mean, from the damage, we all thought
you probably were still smoking.

157
00:07:37,400 --> 00:07:41,037
Cold turkey, five years ago, and
what did I get for my trouble?

158
00:07:41,309 --> 00:07:43,414
I still had to quit my job at the restaurant.

159
00:07:43,490 --> 00:07:45,063
But even sitting, it hurt.

160
00:07:45,201 --> 00:07:46,096
Here you go.

161
00:07:46,239 --> 00:07:48,687
Nobody believed me. They all
said it was in my head.

162
00:07:48,759 --> 00:07:49,876
I've seen the films.

163
00:07:50,351 --> 00:07:51,697
It's not all in your head.

164
00:07:52,482 --> 00:07:53,842
You're right about that.

165
00:07:54,329 --> 00:07:55,154
Hey, come here.

166
00:07:56,357 --> 00:07:58,445
You're too damn young to be a doctor.

167
00:07:58,553 --> 00:08:00,038
- Hey.
- What?

168
00:08:00,975 --> 00:08:02,605
I'm older than I look.

169
00:08:04,124 --> 00:08:06,521
Do you think this is going to work this time?

170
00:08:06,653 --> 00:08:07,968
I think it's your best option.

171
00:08:08,717 --> 00:08:09,822
Straight shooter, huh?

172
00:08:09,895 --> 00:08:10,698
Yes, ma'am.

173
00:08:10,784 --> 00:08:11,957
I like that.

174
00:08:28,638 --> 00:08:29,673
Hi, Mr. Patterson.

175
00:08:30,405 --> 00:08:31,066
Hi.

176
00:08:31,265 --> 00:08:32,612
Hemodynamics stable?

177
00:08:32,739 --> 00:08:35,673
Yeah, map has stayed around 80.
Cardiac output at 5.

178
00:08:35,837 --> 00:08:38,859
- That's good, Dr. Grey?
- That's fine, Mr. Patterson.

179
00:08:39,105 --> 00:08:40,558
But it's not good.

180
00:08:40,743 --> 00:08:43,159
Well, heart surgery takes
a lot out of the patient,

181
00:08:43,221 --> 00:08:45,985
but we're monitoring your wife very carefully,

182
00:08:46,227 --> 00:08:47,645
and she should be fine.

183
00:08:52,835 --> 00:08:55,217
Mr. Sterman, let's see about
getting you out of here today.

184
00:08:55,683 --> 00:08:56,584
How are you feeling?

185
00:08:57,117 --> 00:09:01,539
Pretty okay, except I don't think I ever
want to have a bowel obstruction again.

186
00:09:01,602 --> 00:09:02,304
Really?

187
00:09:02,410 --> 00:09:04,760
We get people in here all the time requesting one.

188
00:09:06,716 --> 00:09:08,236
So, you keeping down clear fluids?

189
00:09:08,544 --> 00:09:11,744
And my all-time favorite
question - have you pooped yet?

190
00:09:11,852 --> 00:09:13,905
I'm not exactly sure.

191
00:09:14,432 --> 00:09:16,972
I think you'd probably know.

192
00:09:18,191 --> 00:09:19,260
Passed gas?

193
00:09:19,977 --> 00:09:20,791
Yes.

194
00:09:21,011 --> 00:09:23,515
Really yes? Because if I bring
in my handy lie detector...

195
00:09:23,613 --> 00:09:24,555
Okay, no.

196
00:09:25,286 --> 00:09:28,152
And I shouldn't try and lie. I know.

197
00:09:28,272 --> 00:09:29,809
I went to medical school.

198
00:09:30,161 --> 00:09:31,338
You went to med school?

199
00:09:31,487 --> 00:09:33,929
Yeah, dropped out my last year at clinical.

200
00:09:34,247 --> 00:09:39,085
Too many hours, and I was staring
into the ice-cold eyes of divorce.

201
00:09:39,147 --> 00:09:39,807
Wow.

202
00:09:40,165 --> 00:09:44,902
Yeah, I do research now, and
I have a life - a family.

203
00:09:45,547 --> 00:09:47,017
No offense. I mean...

204
00:09:47,091 --> 00:09:49,243
No, no, that's okay.

205
00:09:49,377 --> 00:09:51,450
I'm just one of those people
who believe you can have both.

206
00:09:52,198 --> 00:09:53,278
Maybe so.

207
00:09:53,697 --> 00:09:57,083
But your first responsibility's
always gonna be your patient.

208
00:10:20,128 --> 00:10:20,994
Just coffee.

209
00:10:24,014 --> 00:10:24,756
Good.

210
00:10:24,897 --> 00:10:26,215
Okay.

211
00:11:03,658 --> 00:11:06,481
We call this "a spaghetti procedure."

212
00:11:06,589 --> 00:11:09,577
We cut and deflate the bullae

213
00:11:09,768 --> 00:11:12,987
to facilitate gentle manipulation

214
00:11:13,418 --> 00:11:15,394
of Mrs. Drake's lung.

215
00:11:15,951 --> 00:11:19,121
Dr. Bailey, do you see that?

216
00:11:19,813 --> 00:11:20,648
Sir?

217
00:11:22,967 --> 00:11:25,496
Oh, my ever-lovin'...

218
00:11:25,624 --> 00:11:27,192
We need to open her up.

219
00:11:27,400 --> 00:11:28,695
I'm taking out the scope.

220
00:11:30,242 --> 00:11:32,025
You heard him, people. Let's move.

221
00:11:32,100 --> 00:11:33,048
Lights.

222
00:11:34,191 --> 00:11:35,029
10 blade.

223
00:11:35,429 --> 00:11:36,469
- Here you go.
- Retractors.

224
00:11:37,438 --> 00:11:38,162
Retractors.

225
00:11:40,032 --> 00:11:41,056
Scalpel ready.

226
00:11:43,554 --> 00:11:44,355
Towel.

227
00:11:47,177 --> 00:11:48,522
Rib spreader.

228
00:11:52,035 --> 00:11:52,761
Suction.

229
00:12:02,515 --> 00:12:03,763
Is that a towel?

230
00:12:04,150 --> 00:12:05,007
Get a pan.

231
00:12:05,514 --> 00:12:06,538
Where did that come from?

232
00:12:06,601 --> 00:12:09,856
Best guess - her surgery five years ago.

233
00:12:11,284 --> 00:12:14,730
Something careless this way comes.

234
00:12:22,091 --> 00:12:23,899
- A towel?
- Not good.

235
00:12:23,986 --> 00:12:26,685
She complained of pressure on her
chest, but nobody took her seriously.

236
00:12:26,762 --> 00:12:29,034
Not good for the patient,
not good for the hospital.

237
00:12:29,111 --> 00:12:30,125
Not good.

238
00:12:30,899 --> 00:12:32,137
Cristina, hit the files.

239
00:12:32,214 --> 00:12:34,472
Find out everything you can
about that initial operation.

240
00:12:34,538 --> 00:12:35,306
Who was in that room?

241
00:12:35,363 --> 00:12:36,776
Who was responsible for closing?

242
00:12:36,863 --> 00:12:38,235
George, stay with the patient.

243
00:12:38,323 --> 00:12:39,965
Keep her happy. She seems to like you.

244
00:12:40,078 --> 00:12:42,290
Right, okay, um, how long do you think...?

245
00:12:42,772 --> 00:12:45,582
I mean, just technically, I'm off at 6:00.

246
00:12:46,059 --> 00:12:47,037
Am I invited?

247
00:12:47,359 --> 00:12:48,121
Excuse me?

248
00:12:48,255 --> 00:12:49,889
Am I invited to the party?

249
00:12:50,339 --> 00:12:53,901
Well, yeah. Yes, yeah, of course.

250
00:12:57,764 --> 00:12:59,648
What was I supposed to say?

251
00:13:04,728 --> 00:13:07,824
Okay, yeah, great. All right, 14 cases.

252
00:13:08,432 --> 00:13:11,306
What kind? I don't know. Maybe an assortment.

253
00:13:13,365 --> 00:13:14,778
Microbrews - locals.

254
00:13:14,840 --> 00:13:17,747
Make sure they throw in some bar nuts.

255
00:13:17,973 --> 00:13:19,806
I'm ordering office supplies.

256
00:13:19,885 --> 00:13:20,883
Oh, yeah, sure.

257
00:13:22,130 --> 00:13:24,419
Microbrews - local. And throw in some bar nuts.

258
00:13:24,650 --> 00:13:26,287
7:00 would be better than 5:00.

259
00:13:26,373 --> 00:13:27,471
Hey, any luck?

260
00:13:28,490 --> 00:13:30,599
Hey, if I do, will you invite me to the party?

261
00:13:32,938 --> 00:13:34,879
Yeah, great. Okay, thanks.

262
00:13:35,344 --> 00:13:37,756
- Take it easy.
- Mr. Frost.

263
00:13:37,847 --> 00:13:40,035
- Where have you been?!
- We're going to take care of you, all right?

